
00:00:00,374 --> 00:00:03,500
Before building an AI project, you need three things:
Python, a code editor, and a terminal.
7
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,500
Head over to python.org and download the
latest stable version of Python.

8
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:29,500
When you install Python, you also get Pip
—short for "Pip Installs Packages."

9
00:00:29,500 --> 00:00:34,000
Instead of writing everything from scratch,
Pip lets you add database drivers, API frameworks,
or AI libraries instantly.

10
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,500
It also keeps your tools up to date,
ensuring everything works smoothly together.

11
00:00:38,500 --> 00:00:43,000
In simple terms, Pip saves you time by giving you
access to thousands of packages for modern AI apps.

12
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:47,000
Now that you have the tools, we're ready to
create our AI agent.

2
00:00:03,500 --> 00:00:07,000
Create a folder on your desktop called
financial-rag-agents.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,500
Drag and drop this folder into VS Code,
or open it with your preferred editor.

4
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:14,000
I recommend VS Code because it's free,
fully featured, and built for Python and AI.

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,500
You get integrated terminal, error reporting,
and quick project setup out of the box.

13
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:52,000
I'll be using uv to bootstrap the project.
It offers lightning-fast dependency resolution
and optimized build speed.

14
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
It's an excellent choice for quickly setting up
a Python project.

15
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Open the VS Code terminal.
Go to View > Terminal, or press Ctrl + Backtick.

16
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Type: pip install uv

17
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Then type: uv init .
This initializes uv in your current directory.

18
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:12,000
uv has bootstrapped several files for us.
Let's quickly go over what each one does.

19
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:17,000
The .gitignore file tells Git which files or folders
to exclude from version control.

20
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:22,000
This prevents committing sensitive data, large files,
or temporary files to your repository.

21
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Files listed here are never uploaded to GitHub.

22
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Next is .python-version.
This single-line file specifies which Python version to use.

23
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
uv reads this to know which Python to download or use.
pyenv reads it to switch versions automatically.

24
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:39,000
This ensures all team members use the same Python version.

25
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:43,000
main.py is the entry point of your application.
This is the first file that runs.

26
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:47,000
uv creates this as a starting template.

27
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:52,000
Next is pyproject.toml.
This is the central configuration file for modern Python projects.

28
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:57,000
It replaces setup.py, requirements.txt, and setup.cfg.
One file that rules every other.

29
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,000
uv uses this for dependencies, scripts, and settings.

30
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
README.md is the markdown file that describes your project.
This is what you and others see on the GitHub front page.

31
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:11,000
Now let's create a file called .env.
This is a private file containing your actual configuration values.

32
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:16,000
It holds secrets like API keys and passwords.
You must never commit this file to GitHub.

33
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Add .env to your .gitignore so Git ignores it.

34
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,000
If you want a template showing what configuration values are needed
without the actual secrets, create a .env.example file.

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,500
Now let's create our project structure using mkdir -p.

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:09,000
We'll build out our main financial_rag package with subdirectories
for config, storage with repositories, ingestion, parsing,

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,500
processing, retrieval, agents, API routes, monitoring, and security.

4
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:18,000
Then our supporting folders: infrastructure with Docker init,
migrations versions, unit and integration tests,

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:21,500
plus notebooks, scripts, and docs.

6
00:00:21,500 --> 00:00:25,000
One command, and your entire scaffold is ready.

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Now we need to mark these directories as Python packages.

8
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:33,500
We'll use touch to create an __init__.py file in
every directory inside src and tests.

9
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:38,000
Starting with the src directory itself, then financial_rag,
and every subfolder beneath it: agents, api, config, 
ingestion, monitoring, procesing, retrieval, storage, utils

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,500
Then the tests directory, plus unit and integration.
This ensures Python treats them as importable modules.

11
00:00:42,500 --> 00:00:46,000
Run these commands, and our package structure is ready for code.

1
00:20:37,030 --> 00:20:42,000
Before we install dependencies,
let's set up a virtual environment.

2
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:47,000
A virtual environment is an isolated Python workspace
for each project. Here's why it's essential.

3
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:54,000
Imagine two projects needing different versions of Django.
If you install both globally, the second one overwrites the first.

4
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:00,000
Project A needs Django 3.2. Project B needs Django 5.0.
Only one version can exist globally, so they conflict.

5
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:08,000
The solution is a virtual environment per project.
Project A gets its own venv with Django 3.2.

6
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:15,000
Project B gets its own venv with Django 5.0.
They never interfere with each other.

7
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:22,000
Virtual environments solve three real problems:
version conflicts, permission errors, and team collaboration.

8
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:28,000
You can create a virtual environment using uv.
Just type: uv venv

9
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:35,000
Then activate it. On Mac or Linux, type:
source .venv/bin/activate

10
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:41,000
On Windows, type:
.venv\Scripts\activate

11
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:48,000
You can also use the traditional Python command:
python -m venv .venv

12
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:54,000
This creates the same virtual environment.
Activate it the same way we just showed.

13
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:00,000
If you're curious what's inside .venv, it contains
all your isolated dependencies—FastAPI, SQLAlchemy, and more.

14
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:06,000
This folder is large and fully managed by pip.
You never need to interact with it directly.

15
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:12,000
Virtual environments are not optional for professional development.
They are essential.

16
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:18,000
Now let's install our project dependencies using pip.
Type: pip install -e .[dev]

17
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:24,000
The -e flag installs in editable mode,
and [dev] includes our development dependencies.

18
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:30,000
Now that our initial setup is complete,
let's move to the config directory.


[## FILE: src/financial_rag/config/settings.py]

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Let's create our unified settings file.
This is the single source of truth for all configuration.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:10,000
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/config/settings.py

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:15,000
First, imports. We need logging, lru_cache from functools,
Path from pathlib, and Literal from typing.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,000
From Pydantic, we import Field, SecretStr,
computed_field, and model_validator.

5
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
From pydantic_settings, we import BaseSettings
and SettingsConfigDict.

6
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:31,000
Now our Settings class inherits from BaseSettings.

7
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Inside model_config, we tell Pydantic to read from a .env file,
ignore case, ignore extra fields, and validate defaults.

8
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:43,000
First section: Environment.
APP_ENV can be development, staging, production, or testing.
Default is development.

9
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:47,000
APP_NAME and APP_VERSION are simple strings.

10
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Next, derived flags. DEBUG, TESTING, and MOCK_EXTERNAL_APIS.
These are auto-set based on APP_ENV.

11
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:59,000
We use a model validator called apply_env_defaults.
In development or testing, DEBUG becomes True automatically.

12
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:05,000
In testing mode, TESTING and MOCK_EXTERNAL_APIS
both become True.

13
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Now paths. These are computed fields, not stored values.

14
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:17,000
PROJECT_ROOT finds the absolute path where pyproject.toml lives.
It goes up three directories from the current file.

15
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:23,000
DATA_DIR, RAW_DATA_DIR, PROCESSED_DATA_DIR,
and VECTOR_STORE_DIR all derive from PROJECT_ROOT.

16
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Notice VECTOR_STORE_DIR has special logic.
In testing mode, it uses /tmp to avoid polluting real data.

17
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Next, API Server settings. Host, port, and worker count.

18
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:41,000
CORS_ORIGINS is stored as a comma-separated string.
We also provide a computed CORS_ORIGINS_LIST that parses it.

19
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:47,000
Now API keys. OPENAI_API_KEY and GROQ_API_KEY
use SecretStr so they never appear in logs.

20
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Embedding configuration. Provider can be OpenAI or local.
Default is local with the all-MiniLM model.

21
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:59,000
LLM configuration. Provider can be OpenAI, Anthropic, or local.
Default model is GPT 3.5 Turbo.

22
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:05,000
LLM_BASE_URL is set to Groq's endpoint,
giving you fast inference with OpenAI's API format.

23
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:12,000
PostgreSQL with pgvector. Host, port, user,
and a required password with no default.

24
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Without POSTGRES_PASSWORD in your .env file,
the app will refuse to start.

25
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Two computed fields: DATABASE_URL for asyncpg,
and DATABASE_URL_SYNC for Alembic migrations.

26
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Redis configuration follows the same pattern.
Host, port, DB, and a required password.

27
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:36,000
REDIS_URL is computed to format the connection string
with the password embedded.

28
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:43,000
Processing and retrieval settings. Chunk size in tokens,
overlap, top K results, and hybrid search alpha.

29
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:49,000
Logging. Log level and format.
In production, we automatically switch to JSON format
and WARNING level.

30
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:55,000
Rate limiting and API key authentication.
You can enable API keys by setting API_KEY_ENABLED to True.

31
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:01,000
SEC EDGAR ingestion settings. User agent is required
by the SEC. We respect their 10 request per second limit.

32
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Now the validators. First, validate_chunk_settings
ensures overlap is less than chunk size.

33
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:14,000
The main startup validator collects ALL configuration issues
before raising. You see every problem at once,
not one at a time.

34
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:20,000
It checks for missing API keys in production,
and enforces production hardening like specific CORS origins
and DEBUG turned off.

35
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Finally, get_settings is decorated with lru_cache.
The Settings object is instantiated exactly once per process.

36
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:32,000
Now let me explain three critical patterns you just saw.

37
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Pattern one: SecretStr for secrets that never leak.

38
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:44,000
When you print a SecretStr field, you only see asterisks.
It never appears in logs, repr, or error messages.

39
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:50,000
To actually use the value, call get_secret_value.
This forces you to be explicit about where secrets are exposed.

40
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Pattern two: computed_field for derived values.

41
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:02,000
DATABASE_URL is not stored in .env.
It's built on-demand from individual fields.

42
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:08,000
The password is assembled at runtime
and never cached in a plain string that might appear
in a stack trace.

43
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Pattern three: lru_cache with maxsize one.

44
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Settings reads and validates every field from the environment.
That's expensive work. lru_cache ensures it happens once.

45
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:26,000
In tests, you clear the cache before changing
environment variables with get_settings.cache_clear.

46
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:32,000
Our settings file is complete.
Now let's create the config package __init__.
```

