[## FILE: infrastructure/docker/init/create_schema.sql]

135
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:09,000
Now let's create our database initialization script.
We'll put it in infrastructure/docker/init/create_schema.sql

136
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:14,000
This script runs automatically the first time the PostgreSQL container starts.
These statements are idempotent, so they can run safely multiple times.

137
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:20,000
First, we enable four PostgreSQL extensions.
vector for embeddings, uuid-ossp for generating UUIDs.

138
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:26,000
pg_trgm for trigram text search, and btree_gin for advanced indexing.
All use IF NOT EXISTS so they only install once.

139
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:32,000
Now create the filings table.
This stores metadata for each SEC filing we ingest.

140
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:38,000
We have ticker, filing type, fiscal year and quarter,
filed date, source URL, and a unique file hash.

141
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:44,000
Ingested at timestamp with time zone defaults to now.
Is active flag lets us soft-delete filings.

142
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:50,000
A CHECK constraint ensures filing type is one of six allowed values:
10-K, 10-Q, 8-K, 20-F, DEF 14A, or S-1.

143
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:56,000
Three indexes on filings. One on ticker with fiscal year descending.
One on filing type with fiscal year descending.

144
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:02,000
And a partial index on active filings only.
The WHERE clause makes this index smaller and faster.

145
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:08,000
Now the financial_chunks table.
This is our core table for embedding storage.

146
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:14,000
Each chunk belongs to a filing via foreign key to filings.id.
On delete cascade means when a filing is deleted, all its chunks are deleted.

147
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:20,000
We store ticker and filing type denormalized.
This avoids joins for common queries and keeps vector search fast.

148
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:26,000
Chunk_text contains the actual text content.
Token_count is useful for monitoring token usage.

149
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:32,000
The embedding column uses vector data type with 3072 dimensions.
This matches OpenAI's text-embedding-3-large model.

150
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:38,000
Metrics is a JSONB column for chunk-level statistics.
Entities is another JSONB for named entity extraction.

151
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:44,000
Sentiment score ranges from negative 1.0 to positive 1.0.
model_version tracks which embedding model produced the vector.

152
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:50,000
Several indexes on financial_chunks.
Ticker with fiscal year descending, and filing id with section.

153
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:56,000
We also index the JSONB columns metrics and entities using GIN.
GIN indexes are designed for array and JSON data.

154
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,000
Finally, a trigram index on chunk_text.
This enables fast text search without needing a separate search engine.

155
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:08,000
Now the analysis_history table.
This logs every query users make to our RAG system.

156
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:14,000
We store the question, answer, analysis style, and agent type.
Analysis style can be analyst, executive, or risk.

157
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:20,000
Latency in milliseconds helps monitor performance.
Source chunk IDs is a PostgreSQL array of UUIDs.

158
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:26,000
Real time used indicates if we fetched live market data.
Error captures any failures during the query.

159
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:32,000
Session ID lets us group related queries.
Created at with time zone defaults to now.

160
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:38,000
Three indexes on analysis history.
One on ticker with creation time descending.
One on session ID where session ID is not null.

161
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:44,000
And one on agent type with creation time descending,
useful for analyzing which agents are used most.

162
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:50,000
Finally, a schema migrations table.
This tracks which database migrations have been applied.

163
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:56,000
We insert one record for version 001 with a description.
When you add new tables or columns later, add another migration.

164
00:15:56,000 --> 00:16:02,000
This script is now complete.
When Docker starts PostgreSQL, it will run this automatically.

165
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:08,000
You can verify the schema by connecting to the database
and running backslash dt to list tables.

# PHASE 1 — CONTINUED

[## [SECTION: Docker Compose — Development Environment]]

1
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:14,000
Now that we have our schema ready, let's set up the services that will run our database and cache.
We'll use Docker Compose to orchestrate everything.

2
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:20,000
First, let me explain what Docker Compose does.
It lets us define multiple containers that work together as one application.

3
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:26,000
We need two core services to start.
PostgreSQL with the pgvector extension for our vector database.

4
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:32,000
And Redis for caching query results and rate limiting.
Both will run in containers on your machine.

5
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:38,000
We'll also have optional tools you can start if you want.
pgAdmin for browsing the database with a web interface.

6
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And Redis Commander for inspecting what's in your cache.
These are in a separate profile so they don't run by default.

7
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:50,000
Let's create the docker-compose.yml file in the project root.
We'll define reusable anchors first to keep the configuration DRY.

8
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:56,000
x-logging sets up JSON file logging with a max size of 10 megabytes.
It keeps 5 rotated files so logs don't fill up your disk.

9
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:02,000
x-restart sets the restart policy to unless-stopped.
This means containers automatically restart unless you manually stop them.

10
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:08,000
Now healthchecks. These tell Docker when a service is actually ready.
Not just when the container started, but when it can accept traffic.

11
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:14,000
x-postgres-healthcheck uses pg_isready to verify PostgreSQL is accepting connections.
It retries 5 times, waiting 10 seconds between checks.

12
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:20,000
x-redis-healthcheck uses redis-cli ping with the password.
It confirms Redis is responding before other services try to connect.

13
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:26,000
Now the services section. First, PostgreSQL with pgvector.
We use the official image pgvector/pgvector:pg17.

14
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:32,000
The container name comes from an environment variable with a fallback.
If POSTGRES_CONTAINER is not set, it defaults to finrag-postgres.

15
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:38,000
We apply the restart and healthcheck anchors using YAML merge syntax.
The double asterisk and less than less than syntax pulls in both anchors.

16
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:44,000
Environment variables are read from your .env file with fallbacks.
If POSTGRES_DB is not in .env, it defaults to financial_rag.

17
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:50,000
Notice the syntax on POSTGRES_PASSWORD.
The colon question mark means Docker Compose will refuse to start.
If this variable is not set in .env, the command fails immediately.

18
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:56,000
This is fail-fast at startup, not fail-at-connection.
Much better than finding out the password is missing when your app tries to connect.

19
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:02,000
Ports maps the container's internal port 5432 to a host port.
You can override the host port with POSTGRES_PORT in .env.

20
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:08,000
Volumes mounts two things. postgres_data for persistent storage.
This named volume survives container restarts, so your data isn't lost.

21
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:14,000
And a read-only mount of our init directory.
Any dot SQL file in infrastructure/docker/init runs automatically.
On the first container start only.

22
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:20,000
The colon ro means read-only.
The container cannot modify your init scripts.
This is a security best practice.

23
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:26,000
Resource limits let you cap memory and CPU.
Default is 2 gigabytes of memory and 2 CPUs.
With a reservation of 512 megabytes guaranteed.

24
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:32,000
Now Redis. We use the redis:7-alpine image.
Alpine is a lightweight Linux distribution.
The image is around 30 megabytes instead of 300.

25
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:38,000
The command section configures Redis at runtime.
appendonly yes enables persistence to disk.

26
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:44,000
requirepass sets the password from your .env file.
maxmemory limits Redis to 512 megabytes by default.

27
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:50,000
maxmemory-policy allkeys-lru is the eviction policy.
When Redis hits its memory limit, it evicts the least recently used key.

28
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:56,000
This is the correct policy for a cache.
You would never use this for a primary data store like PostgreSQL.

29
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:02,000
Now the tools profile. These services only start if you ask for them.
docker compose up with the profile tools flag.

30
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:08,000
pgAdmin is a web-based PostgreSQL administration tool.
You can browse tables, run queries, and inspect indexes.

31
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:14,000
Email and password come from environment variables.
The password uses the same colon question mark syntax.
It is required.

32
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:20,000
depends_on with condition service_healthy waits for PostgreSQL.
pgAdmin won't start until postgres is ready to accept connections.

33
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:26,000
Redis Commander is a web-based Redis administration tool.
It runs on port 8081 by default.

34
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:32,000
We pass the Redis password through the REDIS_HOSTS variable.
HTTP_USER and HTTP_PASSWORD control access to the web UI.

35
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:38,000
Both tools have memory limits to prevent them from starving core services.
pgAdmin gets 512 megabytes. Redis Commander gets 256 megabytes.

36
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:44,000
Now the network. We create a bridge network called finrag-network.
All services can communicate with each other using container names as hostnames.

37
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:50,000
The subnet is 172.28.0.0 slash 16.
You can override this with NETWORK_SUBNET in .env if there's a conflict.

38
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:56,000
Finally, volumes. These persist data outside the containers.
postgres_data for your database files.

39
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:02,000
redis_data for Redis persistence files.
pgadmin_data for pgAdmin's saved connections and query histories.

40
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:08,000
Named volumes survive docker compose down.
To also delete your data volumes, you need docker compose down minus v.

41
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:14,000
Let me recap the key things to understand.

42
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:20,000
First, the colon question mark syntax on passwords.
Docker Compose will refuse to start if these variables are missing.
Fail-fast, not fail-at-connection.

43
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:26,000
Second, the init directory mount with colon ro.
Any SQL file in infrastructure/docker/init runs once on first start.
The container cannot modify your scripts.

44
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:32,000
Third, Redis eviction policy allkeys-lru.
Least recently used keys are evicted first.
Correct for a cache, wrong for a primary database.

45
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:38,000
To start only the core services, run docker compose up minus d.

46
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:44,000
To include the admin tools, run docker compose with profile tools up minus d.

47
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:50,000
To tear everything down, docker compose down.
To also delete your data volumes, add the minus v flag.

48
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:56,000
Now that our docker-compose.yml is ready,
let's start the services and verify everything works.



[## [SECTION: Infrastructure Verification — Testing PostgreSQL, Extensions, and Redis]]

49
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:02,000
Now that our docker-compose.yml is ready, let's start the services.
We'll use the utility script to make this easier.

50
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:08,000
First, make sure your .env file exists with the required passwords.
POSTGRES_PASSWORD and REDIS_PASSWORD must be set.

51
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:14,000
Then run the start script.
./scripts/start.sh

52
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:20,000
The script does preflight checks first.
It verifies .env exists, docker is installed, and the daemon is running.

53
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:26,000
Then it starts PostgreSQL and Redis.
It waits for both to become healthy before continuing.

54
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:32,000
You should see output like this.
Starting PostgreSQL and Redis...
Waiting for finrag-postgres to be healthy...
✅ finrag-postgres is healthy

55
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:38,000
Waiting for finrag-redis to be healthy...
✅ finrag-redis is healthy

56
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:44,000
The script will then ask if you want to start management tools.
Type y for pgAdmin and Redis Commander if you want them.

57
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:50,000
Once everything is running, let's verify our schema was created correctly.
First, check that all four tables exist.

58
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:56,000
Run this command.
docker exec finrag-postgres psql -U finrag -d financial_rag -c backslash dt

59
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:02,000
You should see four tables.
filings, financial_chunks, analysis_history, and schema_migrations.

60
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:08,000
Now let's verify our PostgreSQL extensions are installed.
Run this command.

61
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:14,000
docker exec finrag-postgres psql -U finrag -d financial_rag -c
SELECT extname FROM pg_extension WHERE extname IN ('vector','pg_trgm','uuid-ossp')

62
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:20,000
You should see three rows returned.
vector, pg_trgm, and uuid-ossp.

63
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:26,000
If any are missing, the init script did not run correctly.
Check that create_schema.sql is in the infrastructure/docker/init directory.

64
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:32,000
Finally, let's verify Redis is responding.
Run this command.

65
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:38,000
docker exec finrag-redis redis-cli -a your-redis-password ping

66
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:44,000
You should get back PONG in all capital letters.
If you get an error, check that REDIS_PASSWORD matches what's in your .env file.

67
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:50,000
If all three checks pass, your infrastructure is ready.
PostgreSQL has the correct schema, extensions are installed, and Redis is responding.

68
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:56,000
Now let's verify our settings work correctly from Python.
Run this quick smoke test.

69
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:02,000
python -c "from financial_rag.config import get_settings; s = get_settings(); print(f'env={s.APP_ENV} debug={s.DEBUG}')"

70
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:08,000
Expected output. env=development debug=True

71
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:14,000
Now verify the database connection URL.
python -c "from financial_rag.config import get_settings; s = get_settings(); print(s.DATABASE_URL.startswith('postgresql+asyncpg://'))"

72
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:20,000
Expected output. True

73
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:26,000
Finally, verify Redis connection.
python -c "from financial_rag.config import get_settings; s = get_settings(); print(s.REDIS_URL.startswith('redis://'))"

74
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:32,000
Expected output. True

75
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:38,000
If all three Python checks pass, your configuration is correct.
Your database and cache clients can connect.

76
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:44,000
If any check fails, review your .env file.
Make sure POSTGRES_PASSWORD and REDIS_PASSWORD are set correctly.

77
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:50,000
Our infrastructure is verified and ready.
We can now start writing tests.



[## [FILE: tests/conftest.py — Pytest Fixtures for Mock Database, Cache, Embeddings, and Test Data]]

78
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:56,000
Now let's set up our test environment.
We'll create tests/conftest.py for shared test fixtures.

79
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:02,000
conftest.py is a special file that pytest recognizes automatically.
Any fixture defined here is available to every test in the suite.

80
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:08,000
First, let's understand what a fixture is.
A fixture is code that runs before your test to set up its environment.

81
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:14,000
Fixtures handle things like database sessions, mock objects,
or environment variables so you don't repeat yourself.

82
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:20,000
Let's start with imports.
We need os for environment variables, and AsyncMock and patch from unittest.mock.

83
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:26,000
From our application, we import get_settings.

84
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:32,000
Now we define VALID_SECRETS, a dictionary with test values for our required secrets.

85
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:38,000
POSTGRES_PASSWORD, REDIS_PASSWORD, and APP_ENV set to testing.
These satisfy the validation that normally requires a .env file.

86
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:44,000
Notice the passwords are at least 32 characters.
This matches the real password requirements without triggering any validation errors.

87
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:50,000
Now the first fixture. clear_settings_cache.
It has autouse equals True, so it runs automatically for every test.

88
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:56,000
Before the test, it calls get_settings.cache_clear.
After the test, it calls it again.

89
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:02,000
This ensures each test gets a fresh Settings instance.
Without this, environment variable changes from one test could leak into the next.

90
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:08,000
Next, the test_env fixture.
It patches os.environ with our VALID_SECRETS dictionary.

91
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:14,000
clear=False means we add to existing environment variables instead of replacing everything.
This allows the test to run even if other environment variables are needed.

92
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:20,000
Why is this important? Our Settings class validates that POSTGRES_PASSWORD
and REDIS_PASSWORD exist. Without this patch, tests would fail because those variables are missing.

93
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:26,000
Now the mock_db_session fixture.
This returns an AsyncMock that simulates a SQLAlchemy async session.

94
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:32,000
We mock execute, commit, and rollback methods.
None of them do real work, but they exist so our code can call them without errors.

95
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:38,000
Using AsyncMock is critical here.
Real database sessions use async await syntax, so our mock must also be async.

96
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:44,000
The mock_cache_client fixture works the same way.
It mocks get, set, delete, and health_check.

97
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:50,000
get returns None by default, meaning cache miss.
set returns True, simulating a successful write.
delete returns True, simulating successful deletion.

98
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:56,000
This allows us to test code that uses Redis
without actually running Redis during the test.

99
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:02,000
Now the sample_embedding fixture.
This returns a list of 384 zeros.

100
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:08,000
Our local embedding model outputs 384-dimension vectors.
This fixture gives us a predictable zero vector for tests.

101
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:14,000
Zero is a safe placeholder because it's unlikely to match any real embedding.
It won't accidentally pass a test that should fail.

102
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:20,000
Finally, the sample_chunk_text fixture.
This returns realistic financial text about Apple's net sales and services revenue.

103
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:26,000
Using realistic text is important.
It ensures our chunking and embedding tests work with real-world content,
not just dummy data like the word test repeated.

104
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:32,000
Let me summarize what each fixture does.

105
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:38,000
clear_settings_cache resets the settings singleton between tests.
test_env patches environment variables with test values.

106
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:44,000
mock_db_session provides a fake database session.
mock_cache_client provides a fake Redis client.

107
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:50,000
sample_embedding gives a zero vector for embedding tests.
sample_chunk_text gives realistic financial text.

108
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:56,000
With these fixtures in place, writing tests becomes much cleaner.
You simply declare the fixture you need in your test function parameter.

109
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:02,000
For example, async def test_something, then mock_db_session as db.
Pytest automatically provides the mock from conftest.

110
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:08,000
Our test fixtures are ready.
Now we can start writing actual tests.



[## [FILE: tests/unit/test_config.py — Unit Tests for Settings, Validators, Computed Fields, and Security]]

111
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:14,000
Now let's write unit tests for our configuration.
We'll create tests/unit/test_config.py

112
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:20,000
These tests verify that our Settings class works correctly
before we build any other part of the application.

113
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:26,000
First, let's understand the structure.
We import os, ClassVar from typing, and patch from unittest.mock.

114
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:32,000
From pytest, we import ValidationError.
From conftest, we import VALID_SECRETS.

115
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:38,000
And from our application, we import Settings and get_settings.

116
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:44,000
First, two fixtures. clear_settings_cache runs automatically before every test.
It clears the lru_cache so environment changes don't leak between tests.

117
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:50,000
The test_settings fixture creates a valid Settings instance for testing.
It patches os.environ with VALID_SECRETS and sets APP_ENV to testing.

118
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:56,000
Now let's look at each test class and what it verifies.

119
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:02,000
TestConfigImport is simple.
It just confirms that get_settings returns a Settings instance.

120
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:08,000
TestRequiredFields checks that every expected field exists.
We have a list of 17 required fields like APP_ENV, POSTGRES_HOST, and CHUNK_SIZE_TOKENS.

121
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:14,000
It also verifies that POSTGRES_PASSWORD is a SecretStr.
This ensures passwords are never accidentally exposed in logs.

122
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:20,000
TestNumericConstraints validates port numbers and chunk settings.

123
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:26,000
API ports, PostgreSQL ports, and Redis ports must be between 1 and 65535.
These are standard valid port ranges.

124
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:32,000
It also checks that chunk overlap is less than chunk size.
If overlap equals or exceeds chunk size, chunking would be broken.

125
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:38,000
TestComputedProperties verifies our derived fields.

126
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:44,000
DATABASE_URL must start with postgresql+asyncpg.
DATABASE_URL_SYNC must start with postgresql+psycopg2.

127
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:50,000
We also check that the URL contains the host, database name, and user.
This confirms the URL is built correctly from individual fields.

128
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:56,000
REDIS_URL must start with redis:// and contain the host and password.
The password is embedded in the URL for authentication.

129
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:02,000
VECTOR_STORE_DIR in testing must use the /tmp directory.
This prevents tests from polluting real data.

130
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:08,000
PROJECT_ROOT must exist and contain the src directory.
This test catches errors in the parents index if the file structure changes.

131
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:14,000
TestSecretSafety ensures secrets never leak.

132
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:20,000
We verify that the raw password value does NOT appear in repr or str output.
If it did, anyone reading logs would see your password.

133
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:26,000
But we also verify that get_secret_value still returns the actual password.
This is how our code accesses secrets when connecting to databases.

134
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:32,000
TestEnvironmentDefaults checks that APP_ENV sets appropriate defaults.

135
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:38,000
In development mode, DEBUG becomes True automatically.
In testing mode, DEBUG, TESTING, and MOCK_EXTERNAL_APIS all become True.

136
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:44,000
TestEnvironmentOverrides verifies we can override any setting via environment variables.

137
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:50,000
For example, setting POSTGRES_HOST changes the database host.
Setting CORS_ORIGINS to a comma-separated string produces a parsed list.

138
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:56,000
The raw CORS_ORIGINS field stores the string as-is.
The computed CORS_ORIGINS_LIST parses it for FastAPI middleware.

139
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:02,000
TestProviderValidation checks that API keys are required when needed.

140
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:08,000
If EMBEDDING_PROVIDER is set to openai but OPENAI_API_KEY is missing,
Settings should raise a ValidationError.

141
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:14,000
This prevents the app from starting with misconfigured providers.
Better to fail at startup than at runtime when the first embedding request comes in.

142
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:20,000
Finally, TestProductionHardening guards against dangerous production settings.

143
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:26,000
If APP_ENV is production and CORS_ORIGINS is an asterisk for wildcard,
Settings raises a ValidationError.

144
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:32,000
Wildcard CORS in production is a security risk.
It allows any website to make requests to your API.

145
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:38,000
To run these tests, execute pytest tests/unit/test_config.py with the minus v flag for verbose output.

146
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:44,000
All tests should pass. If any fail, there's a problem with your Settings class
or your environment configuration.

147
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:50,000
Our config tests are complete. They verify that settings load correctly,
secrets stay secret, computed fields work, and production guards are enforced.



[## [SECTION: Common Errors and Fixes — Phase 1 Troubleshooting]]

148
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:56,000
Before we move to Phase 2, let me walk you through the most common errors
you might encounter in Phase 1 and how to fix them.

149
00:30:56,000 --> 00:31:02,000
Consider this your troubleshooting reference.
When something breaks, come back to this section.

150
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:08,000
Error one. POSTGRES_PASSWORD must be set.
The error message says the variable is required but missing.

151
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:14,000
The cause is that your .env file is either missing,
in the wrong directory, or does not contain the required password.

152
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:20,000
The fix. Check your working directory.
Ensure .env exists in the same directory where you run docker compose.

153
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:26,000
Error two. connection refused on port 5432.
This means your application cannot reach PostgreSQL.

154
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:32,000
The cause is almost always that Docker is not running,
or the containers have not been started.

155
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:38,000
The fix is simple. run docker compose up minus d.
Wait for the containers to become healthy.

156
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:44,000
Error three. ModuleNotFoundError for financial_rag.
Python cannot find your application code.

157
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:50,000
The cause is that you haven't installed your package in editable mode.
Your code exists on disk, but Python doesn't know where to find it.

158
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:56,000
The fix. run pip install minus e dot dev in brackets.
This installs your package in development mode.

159
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:02,000
Error four. asyncio_mode warning from pytest.
Pytest is telling you async tests are not properly configured.

160
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:08,000
The cause is missing pytest-asyncio configuration.
But in our project, the configuration is already in pyproject.toml.

161
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:14,000
The fix. reinstall your development dependencies.
Run pip install minus e dot dev in brackets again.

162
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:20,000
Error five. vector type not found.
PostgreSQL does not recognize the vector data type.

163
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:26,000
The cause is that the pgvector extension was not created.
This happens if your init script did not run.

164
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:32,000
The fix. Check that create_schema.sql is in the infrastructure
docker init directory. If missing, Docker cannot create the extension.

165
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:38,000
You may also need to recreate your containers with docker compose down minus v,
then up minus d to force the init script to run again.

166
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:44,000
Error six. Configuration errors with CHUNK_OVERLAP.
The error says CHUNK_OVERLAP_TOKENS must be less than CHUNK_SIZE_TOKENS.

167
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:50,000
The cause is that your .env file has overlap set to a value
that is equal to or greater than the chunk size.

168
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:56,000
The fix. Reduce CHUNK_OVERLAP_TOKENS below CHUNK_SIZE_TOKENS.
For example, if chunk size is 512, set overlap to 50 or 100.

169
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:02,000
Let me summarize the most important fixes.

170
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:08,000
If Docker fails, check your .env file first.
If Python can't find your code, run pip install minus e dot dev.

171
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:14,000
If PostgreSQL is missing the vector type,
check that your init script is in the correct directory.

172
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:20,000
And if you see configuration validation errors,
check your .env values against the constraints in settings.py.

173
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:26,000
Bookmark this section.
When you hit an error, you'll know exactly where to look.
